    "name": "IDITI_Framework_Validation_Study",
    "description": "Comprehensive three-hypothesis validation of IDITI (Individual Dignity vs Tribal Identity)  framework using pre-labeled control texts across ideological spectrum to establish  discriminative validity, ideological agnosticism, and ground truth alignment.\n",
    "version": "v2.0.0",
    "created": "2025-06-17T00:40:00Z",
    "hypotheses": [
      "H1: Discriminative Validity - IDITI framework can distinguish dignity from tribalism  rhetoric with clear scoring separation (dignity texts >0.6 Dignity well, <0.4 Tribalism  well; tribalism texts >0.6 Tribalism well, <0.4 Dignity well; mixed texts 0.4-0.6 both wells)\n",
      "H2: Ideological Agnosticism - IDITI framework scores based on dignity/tribalism content  rather than conservative/progressive orientation (no significant difference p>0.05 between  conservative and progressive texts within same category)\n",
      "H3: Ground Truth Alignment - Pre-labeled validation texts match expected framework well  responses with extreme controls showing strongest alignment (>0.8) and mixed controls  demonstrating balanced scoring\n"
    ],
    "research_context": "Baseline validation study for newly created IDITI framework establishing performance \nmetrics using complete curated validation corpus (32 texts) to inform iterative corpus \nrefinement and framework tuning in subsequent validation cycles.\n\nBuilding on Social Identity Theory (Tajfel & Turner, 1979) and research on political \ndiscourse analysis, this study tests whether computational text analysis can reliably \ndistinguish between dignity-based and tribalism-based rhetoric across ideological divides.\n",
    "success_criteria": [
      "Clear statistical separation between dignity and tribalism categories (p < 0.05)",
      "Ideological neutrality demonstrated (no significant difference between conservative/progressive within categories)",
